            <text_ac5f
                jcr:created="{Date}2017-03-29T22:46:16.597Z"
                jcr:createdBy="lsloane"
                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2017-07-07T20:05:01.917Z"
                jcr:lastModifiedBy="lsloane"
                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                sling:resourceType="beagle/components/text"
                text="&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>&lt;strong>Greater customer satisfaction&lt;/strong>&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>Microsoft is a leading platform and productivity company and underlying all of its products and services are developers and IT Professionals. The company decided to create a new documentation service for this audience, which focused on the experience as well as the content and how it is created and consumed. Microsoft started rolling out Livefyre across its web portals as part of a general migration of content to a new site—Docs.Microsoft.com. Thus far, 20% of the articles have been migrated and the Livefyre commenting solution already touches 55% of the user base and generates 4,000 comments a month.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>&lt;br>&#xa;Comments are clearly grouped into conversations so readers can easily follow along and jump in with their own thoughts. The Sidenotes feature takes comments into an article by allowing readers to home in on words or phrases and react to specific text anywhere on the page.&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>&lt;br>&#xa;Behind the scenes, Livefyre provides workflows that help article owners manage and publish content. They can quickly spot lively conversations to guide discussions, answer questions, and encourage more feedback with rapid responses. Microsoft can even analyze and follow a commenter’s feedback over time to discover what kind of content attracts quality engagement.&lt;br>&#xa; “For us, quality comments encourage greater interaction from article authors or other readers—people who are asking questions, correcting articles, or giving feedback,” says Gigel Avram, Principal Data Science Manager at Microsoft. “Since adding Livefyre, we’ve seen an increase in quality comments and a 10% to 30% improvement in customer satisfaction.”&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>&lt;br>&#xa;&lt;strong>Building communities&lt;/strong>&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>Analyzing the comments under Livefyre helps Microsoft determine how well articles are meeting customer needs. Article owners can engage and respond to questions in the comments and use this feedback to improve article content. They may add information to an article, write additional articles covering related topics, or restructure content to better speak to readers.&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>“Many of our 800 authors have separate day jobs, so we need ways to point them towards actionable comments that can improve current content and help them write better articles in the future,” says Avram. “The data model provided by Livefyre behind the scenes enabled us to implement a scalable business workflow and let the authors who have the depth of technical domain expertise engage with the customers in a timely manner and with minimum cost to the authors.”&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&lt;span class=&quot;text-light&quot;>&lt;br>&#xa;Based on Livefyre comments, targeted article changes ranging from adding details to posting screenshots improved article ratings by 10%, while changing the focus of an article from specific features to scenarios in which the features are used improved article ratings by 30%. “With Livefyre comments, we also learn about articles that need updating,” says Avram. “For example, each month 50 to 100 corrections might need to be made. The Livefyre workflow allows us to notify the right author and act in a matter of hours from the moment a customer reports a necessary correction.”&lt;br>&#xa;&lt;/span>&lt;/div>&#xa;&lt;div class=&quot;text-5-block&quot;>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div>&#xa;"/>
